{
  "result": "Morning in my city begins with a soft hum, the kind that floats above rooftops before the traffic fully wakes. Vendors roll open metal shutters, releasing the smell of warm bread and dust. Kids in bright uniforms drag backpacks that seem larger than their ambitions, yet their chatter is fearless. I like to walk along the river at this hour. The water is the city\u2019s mirror, but it never keeps a reflection for long. Rowers cut across it, leaving little scars that heal immediately. There is a bench where an old man feeds pigeons with the patience of someone who has already seen every war and invention. Some mornings he speaks to me, telling stories about a bakery he once owned. His voice smells like cinnamon. I wonder whether cities are just collections of such voices, layered like paper, each era scribbling over the last. By noon the streets will be loud and impatient, but in this early hour, the city feels like a friend whispering secrets.\n\nI stop at a small caf\u00e9 where the barista draws a heart in the foam and asks if I\u2019m writing today. I nod, though most days I\u2019m only collecting impressions, like coins dropped into a jar. She says the jar will be heavy someday, and that is enough. Outside, a bus exhales and the sun slides between towers, turning windows into brief flags of fire. I sip my coffee slowly, trying to memorize the flavor before the day rushes in around the corner.",
